    \field{abstract}{%
    Phase II clinical trials in oncology are used to initially evaluate the
  therapeutic efficacy of a new treatment regimen. Simon's two-stage design is
  commonly used for such trials. However, he only focused on the "response
  rate", the proportion of patients experiencing tumor regression. In clinical
  practice, it is preferred of a sequential design to monitor antitumor
  activity as well as toxicity. Conaway and Petroni proposed a method for
  designing phase II trials on the basis of both treatment efficacy and safety,
  which imply an equal weighing of response and toxicity. In this paper, we
  developed an alternative test to cope with the trade-off between safety and
  efficacy. The main idea is to control for the marginal type I errors of
  response rate and toxicity rate separately. We provide guides on searching
